Export Date: 15 February 2026; Cited By: 0; Correspondence Address: P.T. Kumaran; Rajalakshmi Engineering College, Department of Eee, Chennai, Tamilnadu, India; email: thirusenthilkumaran.p@rajalakshmi.edu.in; Conference name: 2025 International Conference on Smart and Sustainable Technology, INCSST 2025; Conference location: Karnataka; Conference date: 2025-07-04 through 2025-07-06
N2  - Breaking and improving adaptive frequency control and dynamic energy distribution in other words AIdriven wireless power transfer (WPT) However, conventional WPT systems are inefficient due to fixed-frequency operation, misalignment losses, and energy distribution is limited by optimal design, and thus have been rarely used in dynamic environment applications like electric vehicle (EV) charging, implantable medical devices or industrial automation. It investigates the application of AI and deep learning to provide real-time frequency tuning and intelligent energy distribution to improve the flexibility, reliability and efficiency of WPT systems. With the ability to predict adjustments to the frequency of wind turbines based on loads, ambient circumstances, and alignment frictions, deep learning algorithms (especially convolutional neural networks (CNNs) and recurrent neural networks (RNNs)) can be performed to achieve maximum power transfer efficiency. Energy balance in communication networks is another area where machine learning has made an impact: RL is used to automatically adapt the strategies for power distribution and learn from past energy demand, dynamically allocating energy resources to avoid loss and maximize efficiency. Implementing resonant inductive coupling-based WPT systems with AI-controlled selfadjusting mechanisms enables real-time supervision and optimization, thus minimizing envelop loss and increasing stability. The next-generation AI-based WPT ecosystem combines sensor networks with cloud-based data processing and embedded AI hardware into a self-learning system that continuously adapts to maximize power transfer efficiency on the fly. The system achieves ultra-low-latency decision-making while ensuring high energy efficiency, through the use of either VLSI-based AI accelerators. Through various experiments, it has also been shown that for AI-based adaptive frequency control, transmission efficiency can be improved by as much as 25% and the use of dynamic energy distribution models up to 30% less than from traditional fixed frequency models. This work advances emerging wireless power systems for applications in smart grids, autonomous robotics, and biomedical implants. Advancements can include the use of quantum machine learning to improve prediction accuracy, the use of neuromorphic computing for performing ultra-lowpower AI inference, as well as blockchain-based energy transactions for secure and decentralized energy distribution. The integration of energy-efficient AI and deep learning into WPT is thus anticipated to offer a transformative solution for optimizing energy delivery in contemporary wireless systems.
