N2  - Quantum computing is progressing rapidly, which brings both new opportunities and significant cybersecurity risks. This matter is particularly crucial since traditional cryptographic systems will be vulnerable to attacks in the quantum era. At the same time, quantum machine learning (QML) is becoming a promising way to improve threat detection, anomaly analysis, and secure communication using quantum-inspired and hybrid learning methods. This paper aims to review essential QML algorithms, including Quantum Support Vector Machines (QSVM), Variational Quantum Circuits (VQC), Quantum Neural Networks (QNN), and Quantum Reinforcement Learning (QRL), while evaluating their prospective contributions to enhancing cybersecurity frameworks. We summarize recent simulation-based and early-stage experimental work, highlight their reported performance on benchmark datasets, and analyze major limitations related to hardware noise, data encoding bottlenecks, and scalability. The review also discusses unresolved issues and potential avenues for future research that could integrate quantum-safe and quantum-enhanced methods. The results indicate that, although the technology is still in its exploratory stage, QML has significant potential to enhance the creation of intelligent, resilient, and quantum-safe cybersecurity ecosystems.
