N2  - The rapid growth of the IoT has led to more cyberattacks on low-power devices. This study presents the IPQCLD model, which uses advanced security measures for future IoT networks to address these issues. It applies data preprocessing methods like Min-Max normalization and LDA, quantum key distribution using the BB84 protocol, and post-quantum cryptography techniques such as Lamport-Diffie one-time signatures. These features enhance authentication, encryption, and attack detection. The Lamport-Diffie method blocks key reuse and authenticates messages, while the BB84 protocol helps detect eavesdropping for secure key exchange. LDA and Min-Max normalization simplify data management and ensure accurate detection. Simulation results show that IPQCLD significantly outperforms baseline models, achieving a precision of 0.95 and a recall rate of 0.90.
