N2  - Blockchain as a Service (BaaS) is, therefore, set to be an essential tool for businesses and developers looking to develop decentralized technologies without the backend burning a hole in their pockets. On the other hand, traditional blockchain use-cases come with drawbacks, including scalability & security issues as well as increased operational expenditure and manual effort for smart contract deployment. BaaS combines with AI and ML Automated smart contract creation, optimization, and management. The research identifies that such ML-driven automation not only predicts the congestion but also optimizes the gas for the smart contracts and also analyzes the vulnerabilities in real-time to improve the efficiency of the smart contracts. Models that generate AI can make possible contracts that execute themselves, self-heal or adapt dynamically, and monitor /maintain in a distributed world where contracts are never static and constantly evolve due to regulatory and operational changes. In addition, the research investigates AI's application within securing blockchain transactions, optimizing consensus mechanisms, and bolstering data integrity. However, issues like computational overhead, compliance with regulations, and attacks from adversaries persist even among these advancements. Further research should aim at designing light weight AI models, interoperability among various blockchain frameworks, and implementing AI based governance models for transparency and efficiency. Optimised BaaS with AI will pave the way for a quantum leap in blockchain adoption by facilitating DApps that are efficient, cost effective, secure and intelligent by enabling innovation across industries such as finance, healthcare, supply chain and government services.
