N2  - The growing intensity and complexity of Distributed Denial-of-Service (DDoS) attacks present vital security threats to Internet of Things (IoT) networks. Centralized solutions to DDoS detection are hampered by scalability, latency, and privacy issues, requiring decentralized and smart solutions. Federated Deep Learning (FDL) has emerged as a viable paradigm, facilitating collaborative model training without revealing raw data. This paper introduces a systematic case study-based investigation of FDL in IoT DDoS detection with a focus on its applications, challenges, and implications. We examine various case studies from a range of IoT environments industrial IoT, smart homes, and critical infrastructure and analyze how FDL is effective against developing attack patterns. Critical issues including heterogeneous data distribution, adversarial robustness, communication overhead, and real-time adaptability are examined and some solutions discussed. Our results reflect the excellence of FDL in providing high detection accuracy with maintained privacy and scalability. We also present future research directions in combining blockchain, reinforcement learning, and quantum computing to provide immunity to FDL-based DDoS detection systems. This research is a worthy reference for researchers as well as practitioners in promoting next-generation intelligent and decentralized IoT security architectures.
