N2  - Healthcare, transportation, and smart cities marked revolutionary growth in the market. They are increasingly relying on the Internet of Things (IoT) that may be appropriately identified with strong privacy and security threats. The decentralized, scalable function of IoT devices leaves them uniquely at risk of cyberattacks or breaches. Many security schemes depend on centralized approaches that just don’t fit in this scenario. A technology like blockchain addresses existing security concerns by facilitating automation using smart contracts and secure communication. This article offers a coherent and thoughtful exposition on the growing security threats to IoT. It addresses gaps in IoT architecture and configuration within pseudo-omnichannels. The discussion further emphasizes latency, energy efficiency of connected devices, and the costs tied to rigid cyber infrastructures that may fall short. The impacts of security are examined using frameworks dependent on artificial intelligence, lightweight blockchains, and post-quantum cryptography as a basis of secure omnichannel architecture. Additionally, the framework addresses universal receipt control and gate access mechanisms as include parts of IoT security.
