N2  - The growth of fake medicines in Bangladesh's medicine market poses a real danger to people's health, makes people lose trust in the products and damages the whole country's healthcare system. To fix this issue, the current supply chain systems are lacking in accountability, traceability, and transparency. A Hyperledger Fabric framework is proposed in this study to help secure and trace the supply of pharmaceutical products in Bangladesh. Through the use of smart contracts and digital identities for users, a permissioned network makes it possible to keep track of medicines from the time they are made until they get to their final users, without anyone being able to change the information along the way. The use of chaincode, secure channels, certificate authorities, and peer organizations helps to automate and secure the transaction process in the architecture. Because each record is uniquely labeled and is cryptographically protected, the system provesthe drugs' identity and keeps them secure. Results from the experiment show that the company was able to spot fake packages and catch counterfeit activity, which made the traceability of all products trustworthy. In the future, designers will look to expand the framework in healthcare fields and include IoT sensors for handling logistics tracking.
