N2  - The current security systems cannot be considered long term sustainable because there is a quantum rate of development of the computing which directly and immediately threatens the classical cryptograph systems. In this respect, the research paper will undertake efforts in giving the concept of an AI-led adaptive mechanism of Quantum Key Distribution (QKD) protocols that will be self-sufficient in guarding and overseeing quantum communication networks against countermeasures towards the constantly evolving threats. The model combines quantum resources management and real-time threat analysis and optimization of dynamic parameter into one flow. Quantum channel noises can be predictedively implemented on machine learning using reinforcement learning, continued intrusion and anomaly detection on neural networks, and independent optimization of the parameters of QKD in dynamical communication systems. Post-quantum cryptography PQC algorithm-based lattice, hash-based and multivariate cryptography are also provided in the system as a backup mechanism to provide the confidence of the hybrid communication environments with the future compatibility of the classical and quantum infrastructural systems. In other cases, the framework will enhance quantum- enhanced blockchain where the AI-enhanced verification enhances the integrity of the distributed registries and resilience in the interparty communication networks. The ethical considerations and the need to have light and interoperative standards are the other considerations since it needs to be able to deploy on a large scale. Instead of calculating the performance standards, the provided research involves the conceptual architecture diagram of the way the predictive AI models can be logically aligned with the natural security features of quantum mechanics to a new generation cryptographic ecosystem that will be able to fight the classical and the quantum adversaries simultaneously.
