N2  - AeroCharge is an IoT-enabled energy harvest device that converts the kinetic energy of airborne particulates and wind turbulence into electricity for creating a decentralized renewable energy source for smart cities. The system can effectively harvest and convert mechanical energy from air pollutants and turbulent airflow using triboelectric and piezoelectric nanogenerators and electromagnetic induction coils integrated with advanced nanotechnology. Continuous sensing of airflow patterns, particulate density, and environmental conditions helps in real-time energy harvesting by optimizing based on the network of IoT sensors. Ultracapacitors store the harvested energy and can wirelessly transfer the held energy to power smart city infrastructure such as streetlights, environmental monitoring sensors as well as communications networks. Additionally, it provides for a blockchain-based energy management system to ensure secure and distributed transactions, and incentive carbon credit collection for sustainable urban development. The proposed solution is to reduce dependence on fossil fuels, and urban carbon footprints, and, secondarily help to improve air quality through airborne particulates. AeroCharge is made experimental with its dynamic environmental conditions and gains in efficiency with experimental simulations and AI-driven optimization. Different challenges and future enhancements are also discussed, such as the hybrid integration of solar and wind power. AeroCharge is a quantum shift to smart cities that will be resilient, and energy efficient.
