DO  - 10.1109/QPAIN66474.2025.11171898
N2  - Modern supply chains face rising pressure to anticipate late shipments, mitigate delivery-risk and respond to volatile customer demand. Leveraging a public 182020 -record 'SMART Supply-Chain' data set, we couple classical statistics with explainable machine learning (ML) to pinpoint the factors that most strongly drive delivery outcomes and sales behaviour. Paired-t tests, Pearson correlation and χ2 analysis reveal: (i) a highly significant gap between scheduled and actual shipping days (p<10-4), (ii) a strong positive link between product price and customer sales (r=0.78), and (iii) shipping-mode and delivery-status associations with late-delivery risk (p<10-4). Six supervised learners - Linear, Ridge and Lasso regression, Random Forest, Decision Tree and Gradient-Boosting - are then benchmarked. Ridge regression attains the best predictive performance (MSE=2.27 × 10-6, MAE=5.7 × 10-4, R2=0.9999) while maintaining model parsimony. To ensure managerial transparency, we generate instance-level explanations with SHAP and LIME, showing that Order-Item-Total, Sales-per-Customer and Order-Item-Discount are the principal drivers of the ridge model's risk forecasts. The integrated framework supplies actionable insight as well as near-perfect accuracy, enabling logistics teams to prioritise high-risk consignments, fine-tune inventory policy and refine shipping-mode selection.
