N2  - Electronic Health Records (EHRs) have thoroughly changed how healthcare works by moving patient information from paper files to secure digital systems.Now,doctors and nurses can quickly access a patient's entire medical history in seconds-ranging from basic information like age and allergies to complex lab results, previous treatments, and specialist notes. Having all this information in one place helps medical teams and also patients make faster, more informed decisions while reducing errors and improving care and safety.Our research synthesizes insights from both internet sources and academic journals to explore the key aspects of EHRs, including Establishing a clear understanding of EHRs and outlining their core features and functionalities compared to traditional paper records. Electronic health records (EHRs) offer real advantages-better care coordination, fewer medical mistakes, and more ways for patients to stay involved in their health. But they are not without their hurdles. Hospitals and clinics still face big challenges when rolling them out, from privacy worries to disruptions in daily workflows. Right now, adoption is growing, but not without bumps along the way.
