N2  - Data security has been a hot topic in e-health since data sharing began. Digitization has sped up operations and increased cyberattack risk. Hackers seem to target medical documents. Past data breaches have driven new security practices to prevent future breaches. Recently developed blockchain technology is a wonderful tool for preserving private data. To protect medical data, the zero trust security model requires all steps, including transmission, to be secured. This paper reviews existing works on similar themes to provide a decentralized and trustless system for safe medical pictures and data sharing and storage. A timely and accurate diagnosis is needed to treat gastrointestinal illnesses like ulcerative colitis, polyps, and esophagitis. To show a Kvasir dataset Autoencoder-deep belief network (AE-DBN) model that automatically classifies gastrointestinal abnormal symptoms. The proposed AE-DBN model combines Autoencoders' unsupervised feature extraction with Deep Belief Networks' hierarchical classification. Experimental results show that the AE-DBN framework efficiently extracts discriminative features, resulting in more accurate and resilient classifications than classic deep learning methods. The results suggest that AE-DBN could be an artificial intelligence-driven gastrointestinal disease diagnostic tool due to its increased feature learning, classification accuracy, and processing efficiency.
