SP  - 1
EP  - 6
SN  - VO  -
DO  - 10.1109/CISCON66933.2025.11337956
N2  - In this research paper, we present new advancements in optimizing digital image processing using modular posit multiplier architectures. The posit number system, a promising alternative to traditional IEEE floatingpoint formats, is especially effective in deep learning and image processing because it manages non-uniform data much more efficiently. However, implementing posits in hardware, particularly for multipliers, is tricky due to the system's flexible bit-widths for mantissas. This flexibility can inadvertently increase energy use when the hardware always accounts for the largest possible bit-width, even if it's not needed for every calculation. To address this, we designed a posit multiplier architecture that boosts energy efficiency and precision. Our solution uses a flexible multiplier divided into smaller, modular units that activate only when necessary, depending on the actual bit-width required by the regime bits. This selective activation dramatically cuts down on power consumption without sacrificing speed or accuracy. The architecture adapts in real time, switching on only what's needed for each computation. For image processing tasks, where computational accuracy and power savings are crucial, this makes it extremely effective. Overall, our design addresses the primary issues with posit arithmetic and paves the way for its application in more complex fields.
