N2  - This paper examines how artificial intelligence can be systematically leveraged to optimize core cybersecurity functions across modern, data-intensive environments. We synthesize and critique AI-driven methods for real-time anomaly detection, adversarially robust classification, and automated incident triage, alongside optimization strategies for firewall rule analysis, policy hardening, and risk-based prioritization. The paper highlights integration patterns that combine machine learning with distributed and edge-centric architectures to reduce latency, improve data locality, and harden telemetry pipelines against tampering. We assess privacy-preserving learning paradigms (e.g., federated and split learning) for cross-domain collaboration without centralizing sensitive data, and evaluate blockchain-backed timestamping for auditability and forensic integrity. The analysis identifies recurring failure modes—model drift, evasion, data quality blind spots—and proposes a research agenda centered on self-learning defense loops, explainable detection, continuous red-teaming, and quantum-resilient cryptographic controls. The result is a consolidated, research-based blueprint for applying AI to measurably enhance detection accuracy, accelerate response, and strengthen end-to-end security assurance in dynamic enterprise and edge settings.
