SN  - 9798331513023
DO  - 10.1109/ICoICC64033.2025.11052047
N2  - In this paper, we propose a hybrid blockchain and deep learning approach for credit card fraud detection, leveraging Slice recurrent neural networks (Slice-RNN) and blockchain technology. The study addresses the challenges posed by highly imbalanced datasets in fraud detection, exemplified by the ECC dataset, which contains only 0.172% fraudulent transactions. We introduce a two-pronged solution: first, employing advanced resampling techniques like SMOTE to tackle class imbalance, and second, utilizing the Slice-RNN architecture to efficiently process temporal data and enhance model convergence through parallelization. To further improve performance, we incorporate multi-head self-attention (MSA) and Bi-SGRU for bidirectional sequence modeling, which significantly boosts classification accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score. The blockchain integration ensures secure, transparent, and real-time monitoring of credit card transactions, with smart contracts enabling automatic fraud detection and alerting. Experimental results demonstrate that the proposed model outperforms existing machine learning techniques, achieving a remarkable 97% accuracy, with enhanced fraud detection capabilities and reduced computational complexity. The hybrid approach presents a robust, scalable solution for detection of fraud in financial systems, offering higher reliability, efficiency, and security compared to traditional methods.
