N2  - Heightened interest in greener energy sources has spurred the design of hydrogen fuel cell microgrids embedded within intelligent smart networks. This article details the concept of an AI-driven hydrogen smart microgrid-termed H2-AISM-leveraging machine learning, streaming-data analysis, and blockchain to elevate energy governance. The architecture incorporates short-term demand prediction, realtime load redistribution, failure-anticipation algorithms, and ensemble learning to maintain superior efficiency despite demand swings. A blockchain fabric enables peer-to-peer energy exchange while safeguarding transaction integrity, and distributed IoT sensors, combined with edge processors, cut latency and boost system responsiveness. Model-driven tests indicate the architecture curtails energy surplus by half, lifts hydrogen utilization by 20 %, and outperforms classic grids in voltage and frequency steadiness. Findings illustrate the promise of AI-enhanced strategies in mitigating demand diversity, storage bottlenecks, and reliability concerns. Guidelines for subsequent studies will pursue the integration of complementary generation and buffering technologies and the infusion of quantum-accelerated machine learning to the hydrogen-centred microgrid ecosystem.
