N2  - Ubiquitous computing, a paradigm envisioned by Mark Weiser, aims to integrate technology seamlessly into everyday life, making computing invisible and omnipresent. This study examines the history and technology behind ubiquitous computing while exploring its practical uses and problems plus future development possibilities. Advancements in multiple technical fields and data processing have built smart environments like homes cities and healthcare. Smart systems depend on sensors and edge processing combined with artificial intelligence to understand their environment. Ubiquitous computing deals with multiple difficulties like expanding its reach across various platforms while making data communication between systems work better and ensuring user privacy and power conservation. Our attention needs to focus on both ethical matters related to data security and user control plus maintaining fairness in systems. New technologies like 6 G communications, bio-integrated sensors, and quantum computers will help systems do more with better performance and solve present difficulties. Ubiquitous computing helps transform many different business sectors by making healthcare better and teaching smarter while improving city planning and environmental protection. As a powerful transformational tool it needs responsible management to support sustainable practices and ethical use for all members of society. Through this research we explore the present capabilities and predicted future path of ubiquitous computing to show how it will drive connected intelligent systems that benefit our world.
