N2  - This paper systematically reviews the current research status of satellite internet security in dynamic task scheduling scenarios, focusing on three key directions: edge intelligence and cloud-edge collaborative computing, blockchain trust mechanisms, and digital watermarking technology. The aim is to systematically summarize the research progress in heterogeneous resource management, security collaboration, and trusted data transmission. In terms of edge computing, a model migration strategy driven by hybrid quantum reinforcement learning and orbit prediction is integrated to achieve adaptive support for dynamic satelliteground services. In terms of trust mechanisms, a lightweight blockchain architecture combined with a federated learning framework provides decentralized support for data consistency and trusted communication under highly dynamic topologies. In terms of content security, the use of frequency-spatial domain fusion watermarking and reinforcement learningdriven offloading strategies effectively achieves data embedding and traceability. However, these technologies still face real-time and stability challenges in low-orbit satellite links with frequency variations and high latency. Looking ahead, AIGC and cognitive security will become key to building a self-evolving security system. Through generative content modeling and attack graph reasoning, intelligent evolution of security mechanisms can be achieved. This paper provides a theoretical foundation and research guidance for building a cross-level, dynamically adaptable satellite internet security architecture.
