JF  - 2025 Global Conference in Emerging Technology, GINOTECH 2025
SP  - 1
EP  - 6
SN  - 9798331507756
DO  - 10.1109/GINOTECH63460.2025.11076879
N2  - The issue of secured data transmission in decentralized and distributed systems is still a challenge that needs to be solved in order to provide privacy of the individual as well as the integrity and security of the data. This makes traditional centralized approaches vulnerable to sensitive information leaks and unauthorized access, thus warranting investigation of more alternative privacy-preserving methodologies. In this paper, we propose a novel secure & privacy-preserving data transmission framework by integrating the advantage of federated learning and the benefit of blockchain technology. This means that data stays on the device and is not shared with the central vote processor, all but eliminating the risks of data centralisation. The incorporation of blockchain technology adds an extra layer of data security with its immutable and transparent nature, along with decentralized consensus algorithms, which prevent unauthorized changes and build trust among entities involved. We present a new framework that utilizes smart contracts to automate the process of regulating data access and enforcing privacy-protective policies while guaranteeing compliance with data governance policies. Furthermore, cryptographic approaches like homomorphic encryption or differential privacy have been integrated into these methodologies to protect data confidentiality and allow secure collaborative learning over distributed nodes. It leverages an optimized consensus algorithm to strike a balance between security and computational efficiency, alleviating latency concerns often related to blockchain solutions. Moreover, experimental assessments validate that the unification of federated learning - supported by blockchain - enhances data protection without compromising model accuracy and scalability over different networks. Results show that this method can both mitigate the risks of centralizing data storage and reduce vulnerability to adversarial attacks, while still keeping people's individual privacy intact without degrading system performance.
ER  - 
TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Survey on Data Plane Security in Software-Defined Networks: Toward Adaptive Security of Data Planes
A1  - Tankovic, Amina
A1  - Dervisevic, Emir
A1  - Mehic, Miralem
A1  - Kaljic, Enio
Y1  - 2025///
KW  - Adaptivity
KW  - data plane
KW  - security
KW  - software-defined networks
JF  - IEEE Access
VL  - 13
SP  - 97058
EP  - 97093
DO  - 10.1109/ACCESS.2025.3575494
N2  - Software-Defined Networking (SDN) is the actual approach in the network design, based on separating the control and data plane. Such architectural model has brought improvements in terms of network monitoring, management and troubleshooting, but has also increased risks related to network security. Security attacks can occur at all SDN layers and disrupt part or the entire network. Existing research is mostly focused on the security of the control plane, since it contains all control logic of SDN networks and thus represents their main part. Although the data plane has many vulnerabilities and can also be a significant source of security threats towards the control plane, it is only partially covered in existing research, without enough details related to differences between methods and implementation techniques which provide security enhancement. In this paper, we present a comprehensive survey on security of the data plane, focusing on the latest advanced solutions. The survey starts with an overview of attacks, threats and affected security attributes in the data plane, classified using common security models: STRIDE, CIA and AAA. After that, we present a detailed analysis of solutions explored in the literature, including the methods used for security enhancement, implementation techniques, experimental environments, their contributions in terms of vulnerabilities that they address, performance analysis and limitations. Through this analysis, we introduce the concept of adaptive security and select several mechanisms which can be used to achieve it. Additionally, we propose possible combinations of presented mechanisms to provide strong, comprehensive solution which should adapt to dynamics of network, attackers and users, and in that way protect the network from different threats and also satisfy the requirements of services which need different levels of security.
ER  - 
