N2  - The widespread accessibility of digital information has led to a surge in fake news, posing a serious global threat. This research tackles the growing concern of misinformation in the Bangla language by proposing a machine learning-based detection model. While fake news detection has gained attention in many languages, Bangla remains underexplored, creating a significant research gap. To address this, the study focuses on developing a robust model using advanced techniques in feature extraction and selection. The research primarily utilizes Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency (TF-IDF) for feature extraction, followed by a selection process aimed at improving model performance. The study highlights the urgent need for accurate fake news detection in Bangla due to its potential social and political consequences. The proposed approach achieves an impressive accuracy of 99.7%, demonstrating the effectiveness of combining TF-IDF with feature selection methods. The findings reveal that integrating sophisticated machine learning techniques enhances the model's ability to distinguish between real and fake news. This work emphasizes the importance of language-specific solutions in the fight against misinformation. Overall, the study presents a promising approach for fake news detection in Bangla and contributes to the broader effort of combating digital misinformation through tailored, datadriven methods.
