N2  - Blockchain technology in the supply chain is set to transform how businesses conduct and transact their businesses. This study explores the transformative potential of blockchain through an analysis of key results in four critical areas: transparency and traceability, efficiency and cost reduction, security and fraud prevention, and interoperability with novel technologies. The prospects of blockchain technology are enhanced transparency and traceability through real-time visibility on the movement of products and exact tracing of product origins and histories. This high level of transparency creates trust among the participants in supply chain and smoothens the dispute resolution. Automation of blockchain has led to substantial efficiency gains as manual tasks and operational delays reduce. Such improvements have reduced the operational costs by 15% making the supply chains more agile and efficient. Through an impressive 98% reduction in security incidents and 95% decrease in fraud incidents after blockchain implementation, security improvements are noticeable. The tamper-resistant properties of blockchain play a huge role in achieving these results and ensure the trust of the stakeholders. The integration of emerging technologies, including the IoT and AI, has only made supply chain capabilities broader. Integrating IoT devices effectively enables real-time data capture and surveillance; AI-powered data analytics give actionable intelligence for data-driven decision-support.
