N2  - The fast development of telemedicine and remote patient monitoring has increased the need for secure and reliable management of health records. This study shows how blockchain technology combined with decentralized encryption techniques, can enhance the security, privacy and access to health information. The paper formulates a blockchain-based architecture in which patients are stored securely and retrieved by encrypted smart contracts, keeping the data intact and private. A decentralized consensus mechanism is used to avoid unauthorized access and tampering. Machine learning models are also incorporated for discrepancy and data recovery. Experimental results indicate that the proposed system enhances data protection, minimizes the risk of cyber attacks, and permitted the patient’s information to the patient’s information from the authorized healthcare providers. Key results indicate that blockchain technology is capable of providing a tamper-evident and transparent medical data environment, addressing telemedicine’s privacy issue. Through the support of distributed encryption, the research facilitates pursuing safe healthcare approaches and thus boosts trust and efficacy in distance-affected individual care. Future visions must emphasize scalability and compliance to support commonly applied blockchain in medicine.
