N2  - 5G networks represent a transformative advancement in telecommunications, offering ultra-reliable low-latency communication (URLLC), enhanced mobile broadband (eMBB), and massive machine-type communication (mMTC). However, these advancements introduce significant cybersecurity and sustainability challenges due to expanded attack surfaces, new threat vectors, and rising energy demands. This paper examines these challenges and proposes solutions, including advanced encryption mechanisms, AI-driven intrusion detection systems, blockchain-based authentication, and zero-trust frameworks. To strengthen validity, the paper references benchmark datasets (e.g., CICIDS 2017, UNSWNB15) and empirical studies from 5G testbeds that demonstrate quantifiable energy savings and intrusion detection accuracy. Additionally, the discussion extends to 6G innovations such as native AI integration, Reconfigurable Intelligent Surfaces (RIS), and semantic communications, positioning sustainability and security as core design principles.
