N2  - In increasingly urbanizing surroundings, smart cities (SCs) are essential for improving urban living, addressing resource constraints, optimizing infrastructure, and utilizing technology for efficiency, sustainability, and a higher standard of living. Because quantum cryptography (QC) may offer appropriate performance for security for various applications, it is gaining importance in both the scientific and business areas. SCs produce a huge deal of data because of the extensive use of networks, sensors, and linked devices. Thus, SC security issues include cyber threats, data security, Internet of Smart City Things (IoSCT) vulnerabilities, and urban infrastructure dangers, necessitating strong solutions to protect residents, digital assets, and vital services. Some options include cybersecurity measures, data signatures, threat detection strategies, and standardized security procedures to promote a robust and safe SC ecosystem. Unfortunately, existing systems are still vulnerable to security threats, mainly due to the lack of fast and effective security techniques. In order to combat these security loopholes, this research work proposes a SC security system (PSCSS), grounded in QC, FALCON signatures (FS, QKD) technology, RF and QBoost. Use of QC helps in effective precautions to be maintained for security. In addition, because FS does provide reliable safety to protect the data received through the SC nodes from tampering. In this paradigm, QKD underpins the PSCSS, offering public and private keys to all SC nodes reliably and securely. To sum up, the fusion of RF and QBoost is beneficial when it comes to identifying suspicious data in PSCSS. The viability of the proposed system is illustrated through theoretical performance, security analysis and comparison of the SC system with state-of-theart security algorithms. The theoretical results show that our system achieves a better trade-off between performance and security than existing systems.
ER  - 
