N2  - The sudden convergence of Metaverse and Artificial Intelligence (AI) technologies has transformed individuals' interactions, socialization, and online transactions within virtual ecosystems. With the increasing integration of AI into Metaverse platforms so that smart agents, emotion analysis, and live adaptation are feasible, there come immediate concerns for data privacy, digital identity, and secure authentication of users. This article provides an extensive overview of the existing state of data protection measures in AI-based Metaverse systems, with emphasis on issues like deep-fake-induced identity creation, biometric exposure, centralized control of identities, and the absence of standardized security protocols. To tackle these challenges, this study reviewed a variety of privacy-friendly methods such as biometric and behavior-based authentication, decentralized identity platforms based on blockchain, transparent AI for responsible transparency, and enhanced cryptographic solutions like quantum signatures. The authors also investigate the shortfalls of current methods, identify important research gaps, and suggest directions for scalable, interoperable, and ethically sound security frameworks. The results highlight the necessity of interdisciplinary collaboration and embracement of user-centric, adaptive protection approaches toward developing trusted, secure, and inclusive Metaverse ecosystems.
