N1  - Export Date: 15 February 2026; Cited By: 0; Correspondence Address: A. Khanna; Data Protection Lead, Pacific Gas and Electric, Plano, United States; email: mailtoanirudh@gmail.com; Conference name: International Conference on Sustainable Engineering and Advanced Technology, ICSEAT 2024; Conference location: Kuala Lumpur; Conference date: 2024-08-05 through 2024-08-06; Conference sponsors: Anton Paar; Ng, Arlene Tan and Leong Advocates Soliditors; Raffles University; Revlogi Materials
N2  - The technology perspective of the energy sector is growing increasingly unfavorable because of mounting trends and emerging threats. Businesses must stay abreast of technological advancements, thus being exposed to highly technical cyber threats, more so ransomware attacks. Some emerging trends are AI and ML, the Internet of Things (IoT), cloud computing, and blockchain. These advancements also bring in many threats, like cyber-physical attacks, advanced persistent threats (APTs), and quantum vulnerabilities. As for now, ransomware attacks are predicted to become more sophisticated, and AI and ML will be used for altercation and defense. Likely, the connectivity of IoT devices and the use of the new generation of the network, 5G, will make organizations more vulnerable. To compete against these risks, all energy sector business entities must implement a secure information protection environment and secure their 5G constituents by incorporating perpetual identity authentication, sophisticated encryption, and safe IoT gadget characteristics. As for measures to counter these threats, there is a suggestion to diversify cybersecurity approaches through artificial intelligence-based threat identification and quantum-safe cryptography, as well as enhance cooperation between the countries with the assistance of threat information exchange. Besides, the increasing talent shortage needs attention, and we can advise strategic measures for the future. Failing to do so could mean that organizations operating in the energy sector will keep experiencing challenging times in protecting their structures from future ransomware attacks.
