N1  - Export Date: 15 February 2026; Cited By: 0; Correspondence Address: O. Al Jadaan; Ras Al Khaimah Medical and Health Sciences University, Ras Al-Khaimah, United Arab Emirates; email: ojadaan@rakmhsu.ac.ae; Conference name: International Conference on Business and Technology, ICBT 2024; Conference location: Oxford; Conference date: 2024-11-21 through 2024-11-22
N2  - The healthcare industry has unfortunately become a main target for increased cyberattacks. Over a 100 million healthcare records worldwide have already happened in 2023. This shows how fragile the healthcare sector has become, despite it holding a huge role in the protection against patients’ health. There are a few factors that have contributed to this; among them are complex health data, outdated technical architecture, and most recently, the rapid growth of Internet of Things (IoT) devices across hospitals and clinics. Such needs among many others leave healthcare organizations not shielded against cyber-attack risk and having patient care crippled and causing substantial losses. In other words, that makes the call for stronger cybersecurity louder now than ever. This paper discusses what are considered to be today's main challenges of healthcare cybersecurity. These are dependence on legacy systems, demanding regulatory requirements such as HIPAA and GDPR, and the greater use of IoT and telemedicine which constitute inalienable parts of health today. Furthermore, it discusses various state-of-the-art technological solutions, such as encryption and blockchain with the inclusion of Artificial Intelligence that allows powering up highly improved healthcare defences. However, technology is not the solution alone. Moreover, the paper discusses the development of policies to improve employee training and ensure cybersecurity standards are followed. Real-world cases are also focused upon, such as the attack of WannaCry on the UK's National Health Service, to emphasize the importance of a robust and scalable cybersecurity implementation. This underlines the necessity for healthcare providers to adopt a multi-layered approach to cybersecurity. The future is bright with possibilities—AI-powered threat detection and quantum encryption could completely alter how patient data is protected as healthcare continues to move into a more digital world.
