N2  - Phishing attacks, which trick users into revealing sensitive information in order to harvest amounts of sensitive or valuable data, represent one of the most enduring cybersecurity issues that affect both individuals and organizations alike. Conventional security measures such as rule-based filtering and blacklisting agents are insufficient in detecting advanced phishing attacks that utilize social engineering and obfuscation techniques. In this research, an AI-based approach is proposed for the improvement of the email security where the machine learning (ML) techniques are utilized for phishing attack detection in real time. Analyzes email headers, body content, embedded URLs, and user behavior patterns using a range of ML techniques such as the supervised learning, deep learning and NLP. We propose a novel hybrid AI model comprising of feature engineering, anomaly detection and reinforcement learning to enhance detection accuracy and reduce false positive rates. According to experimental results, phishing detection systems using ML are proven to be quicker, more efficient, and better able to adapt to new attack patterns compared to traditional ones. By integrating XAI, security solutions powered by AI become more interpretable for cybersecurity professionals due to increased transparency. While there are various challenges including resistant attacks and resource factor calculations, future work can include integrations such as Blockchain-based email authentication, federated learning for decentralized sharing of threat intelligence systems, quantum-resistant cryptographic techniques, to better secure the underlying systems against Phishing attack.
