N1  - Export Date: 15 February 2026; Cited By: 0; Correspondence Address: Z.N. Rashid; Sulaimani Polytechnic University, Technical College of Informatics, Computer Networks Department, Iraq; email: zryan.rashid@spu.edu.iq
N2  - Smart cities and industries, as well as smart systems for disaster control, have utilized the Internet of Things (IoT) to change the digital environment drastically. Still, the widespread use of different architectures, a wide range of applications, and the variety of network protocols make it harder to achieve reliable, safe, and energy-efficient communication in the IoT. Existing IoT reference architectures, rigid in the sense that they are protocol-oriented, are ill-suited for providing real-time responses and fully extensible support. This paper introduces an AI-driven multiprotocol optimization framework that can counter these challenges. This framework employs multi-protocol adaptation to ensure proper interconnectivity among various IoT systems, while also incorporating reinforcement learning into the routing path to detect anomalies. Solar panels and batteries enhance energy efficiency by utilizing the Pelican Optimization Algorithm (POA), while smart grids and blockchain technology add cybersecurity to the system. The collected data, derived from both simulation (using OMNeT++) and real-world deployments across smart city, industrial IoT, and disaster recovery environments, reveals that the framework outperforms benchmark solutions— namely, CIC-SIoT, Immersive Edge IoT, and traditional static-routing IoT frameworks—by 30% in latency, 25% in throughput, 40% in energy efficiency, and 95% in threat detection success rate.”Smart city, industrial IoT, and disaster recovery use cases explain its flexibility and expansiveness. The author constructs this framework to ensure full scalability, security, and efficiency for next-generation IoT networks, incorporating edge-cloud collaboration, highperformance AI models, and a modular architecture. The author will study the integration with new technologies, such as 6G and quantum processing, to an advanced level in future studies.
