N1  - Export Date: 15 February 2026; Cited By: 0; Correspondence Address: I. Ud Din; The University of Haripur, Department of Information Technology, Pakistan; email: ikramuddin205@yahoo.com; A. Almogren; King Saud University, College of Computer and Information Sciences, Department of Computer Science, Riyadh, 11633, Saudi Arabia; email: ahalmogren@ksu.edu.sa; CODEN: ITCED
N2  - The rapid advancement of quantum computing and the increasing complexity of Consumer Internet of Things (CIoT) systems necessitate trust assessment frameworks that are stable, scalable, and quantum-resilient. This study proposes a Post-Quantum Secure AI-Blockchain Framework for evaluating trustworthiness in CIoT environments. The model integrates a hybrid Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) and Bidirectional Long Short-Term Memory (BiLSTM) network with self-attention mechanisms for anomaly detection, Federated trust learning for decentralized trust computation, and Post-Quantum Cryptographic primitives, including NTRUEncrypt and FrodoKEM, for encryption resilience against quantum threats. To further enhance stability, Generative Adversarial Networks are used for adversarial data augmentation, and Multi-Objective Evolutionary Optimization with Reinforcement Learning is applied to improve edge-level resource efficiency. The Experiments demonstrate high classification performance with respect to accuracy, F1-score, and ROC-AUC. Blockchain-based performance shows 850 transactions per second, a 70% reduction in latency, and a 12× gain in energy efficiency compared to conventional architectures. These results confirm that the proposed framework offers a novel, secure, and efficient solution for quantum-resilient trust management in next-generation CIoT ecosystems.
