N1  - Export Date: 15 February 2026; Cited By: 20; Correspondence Address: A.K. Ghosh; IES College Of Technology, Department of Electronics &amp; Communication Engineering, Bhopal, M. P., 462044, India; email: amarjeet.research@iesuniversity.ac.in; Conference name: 2024 IEEE International Conference on Intelligent Systems and Advanced Applications, ICISAA 2024; Conference location: Pune; Conference date: 2024-10-25 through 2024-10-26; Conference sponsors: IEEE
N2  - Industrial cyber-physical systems (CPS) must be secure at a time when automation and linkages are crucial to business. This study uses powerful AI to make industrial CPS safer than previous approaches. The proposed response improves speed metrics, making it a good alternative for protecting these vital systems. RNNs detect unusual things, Kmeans grouping finds patterns, and Q-learning changes our responses. These systems are adept at identifying odd behavior, grouping tendencies, and altering threat responses. Our solution outperforms traditional security approaches in many key performance areas. The new method's threat detection accuracy is 98.2%, up from 94.5%. The false positive rate drops by 40.0%, reducing needless warnings and issues. This reduces the false negative rate by 43.8%, making threat identification more sensitive. Our method's response time has fallen by 33.3%, making it responsive to new threats. We utilize system resources more efficiently by 21.4%. Scalability is 'high,' meaning it adapts to business changes. We proposed a cutting-edge way to make commercial CPS safer. Its excellent AI algorithms defend critical industrial equipment from cyber-physical attacks. Threat detection outperforms previous techniques in accuracy, false alarms, reaction time, resource use, and growth. As businesses employ connected systems, our technique protects industrial operations effectively and preventatively.
