N2  - As cyber threats targeting aerospace systems grow in sophistication and frequency, the development of comprehensive defense mechanisms has become a paramount concern for stakeholders in this critical industry. This discussion explores the multifaceted landscape of aerospace cybersecurity, emphasizing the urgent need for advanced detection, isolation, and containment strategies tailored to the unique challenges of aerospace systems. The convergence of technologies such as artificial intelligence (AI), blockchain, quantum cryptography, and biomimicry-inspired architectures forms the backbone of this research, providing a holistic approach to safeguarding aerospace operations. At the core of this study is an in-depth examination of AI-driven anomaly detection systems, which leverage machine learning algorithms to identify and mitigate emerging threats in real-time. Reinforcement learning (RL) techniques and generative adversarial networks (GANs) are discussed as transformative tools for simulating attack scenarios and developing adaptive defense strategies. The integration of blockchain technology is explored for its ability to provide immutable, tamper-proof logging mechanisms, ensuring transparency and accountability during cyber incidents. Moreover, resilient system architectures inspired by biological systems introduce novel paradigms for redundancy and adaptability, drawing parallels between natural resilience mechanisms and engineered solutions. The discussion also ventures into future-facing technologies that promise to redefine the aerospace cybersecurity landscape. Quantum cryptography, with its theoretically unbreakable encryption capabilities via Quantum Key Distribution (QKD), is highlighted as a critical solution for securing satellite communications and protecting sensitive data against quantum computing threats. Homomorphic encryption is examined as a breakthrough for enabling secure computations on encrypted data, eliminating the need for decryption and mitigating data exposure risks in cloud-based environments. Federated learning and edge AI emerge as decentralized frameworks for collaborative threat detection and real-time decision-making, addressing the latency and privacy challenges inherent to aerospace systems.
