N1  - Export Date: 15 February 2026; Cited By: 2; Correspondence Address: S.V. Chaudhari; Datta Meghe Institute of Higher Education and Research, Faculty of Engineering and Technology, Wardha, Maharashtra, India; email: shreyash712004@gmail.com; Conference name: 3rd International Conference on Electronics and Renewable Systems, ICEARS 2025; Conference location: Tuticorin; Conference date: 2025-02-11 through 2025-02-13
N2  - Traditional voting methods have been marred by high prices, identity theft, manipulation of results, and logistical inefficiencies, which are a huge threat to the integrity of democratic processes. Alternative systems like e-voting are plagued by challenges such as data integrity difficulties, lack of transparency, and central server vulnerabilities. Blockchain technology has emerged as a game-changer in overcoming such constraints with its transparent, immutable, and decentralized design. The paper reviews over 15 studies based on progress in voter authentication, scalability, security, and privacy-preserving strategies such as incorporation of biometric technologies, smart contracts, and hybrid blockchain networks with regards to blockchain-based electronic voting systems. Blockchain-based voting has several disadvantages, including high transaction costs, scalability issues, and a need for broad user confidence and legal frameworks. The goal of emerging technologies such as Practical Byzantine Fault Tolerance (PBFT), Ethereum Layer 2, and homomorphic encryption is to overcome these hurdles and make blockchain-based e-voting a reality for large-scale elections. This review highlights the flaws of the current systems, indicates some further research directions, and underlines how important it is to integrate blockchain with state-of-the-art technologies such as artificial intelligence, the Internet of Things, and quantum-resistant cryptography. Blockchain technology can change the face of modern voting processes by addressing problems of increasing public trust, security, and transparency.
