N1  - Export Date: 15 February 2026; Cited By: 0; Correspondence Address: J. Hu; Guangzhou Huali College, Guangzhou, Guangdong, China; email: Rayson1113@163.com; Conference name: 3rd International Conference on Data Science and Information System, ICDSIS 2025; Conference location: Hassan; Conference date: 2025-05-16 through 2025-05-17
N2  - This paper addresses the security and privacy challenges in digital currency transactions caused by traditional encryption limitations and complex network attacks. To tackle these issues, we propose an integrated framework combining homomorphic encryption for privacy-preserving data processing, quantum encryption for ultra-secure transmission, blockchain for decentralized transparent storage, and graph neural networks (GNN) for intelligent transaction analysis. The methodology innovatively applies quantum-resistant encryption to counter future threats while enabling encrypted computations through homomorphic algorithms. Blockchain ensures immutable transaction records, and GNN dynamically models transaction networks to detect money laundering patterns through graph convolution operations. Experimental results demonstrate 91% F1-score in anomaly detection using GNN, outperforming traditional methods by 4.9%, with quantum encryption reducing man-in-middle attack risks by 98%. The framework achieves 92.7% accuracy in large-scale transaction monitoring while maintaining reasonable encryption/decryption latency (0.14s per 100 transactions). This synergistic approach effectively balances security, privacy, and regulatory efficiency, providing a robust solution for next-generation digital currency systems.
