N1  - Export Date: 15 February 2026; Cited By: 0; Correspondence Address: G. Pandian; HuMetis Group Inc., Kingston, 4478 Route 27, Suite 201, 08528, United States; email: ganesmoorthy@gmail.com; Conference name: 2025 IEEE International Global Conference in Emerging Technology, GINOTECH 2025; Conference location: Pune; Conference date: 2025-05-09 through 2025-05-11
N2  - The rapid expansion of the Internet of Things (IoT) poses essential security challenges, especially in relation to device authentication and trust management. Moreover, centralized authentication approaches pose significant single points of failure, latency issues, as well as risks due to DDoS (Distributed-Denial-of-Service) and MITM (man-in-the- middle) attacks. In this work, we aim to overcome these limitations and propose a Decentralized Trust Management System based on the Blockchain and Machine Learning for real-time device authentication in an IoT network. It is important to acknowledge that the permissioned integration of blockchain ensures immutability, transparency, and decentralized authority without a centralized trust authority. At the same time, machine learning models are used to compute device trust scores dynamically, relying on the behavioral analysis, the anomalies detected, and the historical interactions. This mechanism uses smart contracts to facilitate the trust assessment process and authenticate devices, therefore minimizing third-party reliance. A consensus mechanism adapted to IoT scenarios, like lightweight Proof-of- Authority (PoA) or Delegated Proof-of-Stake (DPoS), is adopted to maximize energy efficiency and accelerate transaction validation. The machine learning aspect involves using various algorithms for anomaly detection, including Support Vector Machines (SVM), Random Forest (RF), and Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks to spot malicious or compromised devices in real-time. We conduct a proof of concept on a simulated IoT testbed to evaluate the effectiveness of the DTMS against unauthorized access, authentication latency, and network resilience. Evaluation, including accuracy, precision, recall and computational overhead show that integration of blockchain and machine learning can substantially secure and scalable IoT authentication frameworks. This will help improve the security of the IoT networks, as the presented trust-based, decentralized authentication framework autonomously identifies and neutralizes security attacks. In the future, optimialization in federated learning for distributed trust calculation, implementation of zero-knowledge proofs for privacy-preserving authentication, and the use of quantum-resistant cryptographic techniques in a blockchain system may provide richer development in this domain. The results underscore the promise of the blockchain-based decentralized, trust management systems for establishing a secure, robust and scalable security paradigm for next-generation, IoT networks.
