N2  - This study proposes a novel multi-layered framework (MLF) to address privacy and security concerns in blockchain-based systems used in the smart healthcare industry. The framework addresses the challenge of using rare disease data for secure processing and analysis while preserving patient privacy and the critical challenges in network security. To achieve this, the study integrates Federated Learning (FL) and Differential Privacy (DP) techniques into the MLF to protect sensitive data and preserve individual identities during analysis. In DP, adaptive noise distribution is used as a performance improvement method to optimize model accuracy loss. In addition, the framework utilizes a quantum-resistant Module Lattice-Based Key-Encapsulation Mechanism (ML-KEM) for a secure communication architecture. The proposed solution offers a hybrid cryptographic approach by combining ML-KEM with Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) for key encapsulation. In addition, it includes blockchain integration, IPFS, and Web3-based architecture for low transaction costs and overhead. In the DP-integrated 200-round FL process, the model achieves a 98.74% accuracy rate thanks to the dynamic DP mechanism implemented to optimize the privacy and data usefulness trade-off. Experimental results show that the proposed framework achieves high accuracy rates in health analytics tasks, resists attacks, and provides privacy guarantees.
