N2  - Decentralized social networks (DSNs) face persistent challenges, including trust deficits, malicious behaviors, and scalability issues. Existing trust management (TM) and consensus mechanisms often fail to adapt to the dynamic nature of these networks. To address these challenges, this paper introduces TC-PBFT (Trust Cluster Practical Byzantine Fault Tolerance), an optimized extension of the PBFT consensus algorithm. TC-PBFT enhances the consensus process by incorporating dynamic trust metrics updated during the consensus phases. These metrics include availability, which measures responsiveness to critical messages; authenticity, which detects and penalizes tampered communications; and response delay, which rewards faster nodes. Trust scores are computed using the enhanced EigenTrust algorithm (ModET-FC), which integrates social network feedback to enable multi-level trust propagation, enhance credibility scoring, and improve adaptability and resilience in decentralized networks. This approach ensures a comprehensive evaluation of node trustworthiness in DSNs. By refining the initialization trust values derived from the ModET-FC algorithm, TC-PBFT ensures reliable and adaptive participation of nodes in consensus operations. Simulation results demonstrate that TC-PBFT outperforms traditional protocols, such as PBFT and T-PBFT, in trust accuracy, operational efficiency, scalability, and overall system performance across various scenarios. Experimental validation further confirms that TC-PBFT significantly enhances system efficiency while maintaining improvements in system throughput, transaction latency, and communication overhead. This approach strengthens trust evaluation and consensus mechanisms in DSNs, providing a reliable and efficient foundation for modern decentralized networks.
ER  - 
