VL  - 123
SP  - 110028
EP  - 110028
DO  - 10.1016/j.compeleceng.2024.110028
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0045790624009534
N2  - The quantum crisis presents a grave threat to patient health, the vast and lucrative healthcare industry, society, and national security. If current cryptographic systems protecting the security and privacy of medical technologies become obsolete, patient care could be compromised. Cyber attackers might disrupt hospital networks, delaying urgent care, or tamper with critical medical devices like pacemakers and insulin pumps, risking severe illness or death. As communication technologies advance, secure authentication has become a vital requirement for protecting sensitive healthcare information from unauthorized access. Authentication schemes are generally classified as individual-oriented or group-oriented and often rely on traditional mathematical assumptions, such as the difficulty of integer factorization into large prime numbers or solving discrete logarithms. However, these assumptions can be efficiently broken using quantum computing. To address these challenges, we propose a novel lattice-based post-quantum group authentication protocol for healthcare applications. Security analysis using a random oracle model confirms its resilience against replay, stolen-table, and man-in-the-middle attacks. Comparative performance evaluations highlight the protocol's enhanced security, lower computational requirements, and reduced communication overhead compared to existing solutions.
