N2  - While the first three industrial revolutions were driven by revolutionary core technologies, the Fourth Industrial Revolution is characterised by clusters of digital-intelligent technologies. Compared with traditional business models, the modern business landscape, which is empowered by these technologies, exhibits trends and characteristics such as networking, digitisation, intelligence, platformisation, decentralisation and personalisation. This transformation is driven by three main mechanisms: the self-reinforcement of digital-intelligent technologies, their mutual empowerment and the amplification of network effects through smartphone connectivity. However, the widespread adoption of these technologies poses socio-economic challenges, including issues around privacy protection, information cocoons, platform monopolies and digital taxation. Specific governance measures have been proposed to address each of these issues.
