T3  - CISAI '25
SP  - 1550
EP  - 1556
CY  - New York, NY, USA
SN  - 9798400718748
DO  - 10.1145/3773365.3773608
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1145/3773365.3773608
N2  - The limitations of traditional group signature schemes in dynamic member management and centralized trust models restrict their application in resource-constrained scenarios. Existing schemes face challenges such as the centralized trust problem of the PKI system and high costs in dynamic member management. This paper proposes a novel group signature scheme based on CPK (Combined Public Key) and elliptic curve Schnorr signature. The scheme uses the (t, m) threshold mechanism to achieve distributed management of group administrator keys, leverages the characteristics of CPK to address the trust concentration issue in traditional PKI, and significantly reduces certificate management costs. By combining the Schnorr signature algorithm, a lightweight design is realized on the SECP256k1 elliptic curve. The system's security is enhanced by introducing timestamp, random number, and version control mechanisms, and dynamic member management with O(1) complexity is achieved. Benchmark tests show that the system exhibits good computational efficiency within the member scale range of 100 to 10,000: the signature generation algorithm takes milliseconds (0.8ms-1.3ms), and the verification algorithm response time is stable in the range of 1.2-2.2 milliseconds. This scheme strictly meets the core security properties of group signatures, such as anonymity, unforgeability, and traceability, and is suitable for large-scale dynamic group authentication applications in resource-constrained environments such as IoT devices and mobile terminals.
ER  - 
