N2  - As China accelerates the development of digital government, this field has become a key focus in academic research. Using CiteSpace visualization tools and an enhanced mediation centrality algorithm, this study systematically analyzed over 1,100 digital government research papers from CNKI's "Peking University Core"and "CSSCI"databases between 2018 and May 2025. The research aims to map the current knowledge landscape of domestic digital government studies and forecast future trends. Findings reveal rapid growth in related literature, demonstrating the significant impact of digital government initiatives on both academia and policy implementation. The study also explores the intrinsic connection between research trends and policy execution. Despite high participation from research institutions and scholars, the relatively loose collaborative network indicates the absence of leading core research forces in this field. Finally, the paper proposes key directions for future digital government research: establishing scientific evaluation systems, deepening empirical analysis, promoting theoretical innovation, and enhancing data empowerment and collaborative governance in digital government development.
