DO  - 10.1145/3709020.3735357
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1145/3709020.3735357
N2  - The growing abundance of digital health records offers remarkable pathways for AI-driven medical advancements, yet this precious resource calls for strong safeguards to protect sensitive patient data - a trust we are bound to honor. In this study, we present and meticulously evaluate a complete framework. This system is crafted to enable accurate medical predictions directly on encrypted data, in concert with a novel and secure approach for managing cryptographic keys (KMS). Our proposed solution integrates batched Cheon-Kim-Kim-Song (CKKS) homomorphic encryption (HE) for predictive modeling - specifically logistic regression - with a hybrid KMS. The proposed work employs HashiCorp Vault for the secure off-chain keeping of cryptographic keys. Access is ensured by a Hyperledger Fabric distributed ledger (DLT), which enforces Zero Trust and Four-Eye access control principles. We rigorously tested this integrated system using a medical dataset, carefully considering the intricate balance of trade-offs across different security levels (192-bit and 256-bit), various polynomial approximations for sigmoid functions, diverse batch sizes, prediction accuracy, and overall performance. The outcomes reveal that predictions made using homomorphic encryption achieved accuracy comparable to those from unencrypted (plaintext) data. This affirms its potential utility in clinical settings without undue compromise on privacy - a vital consideration. Our study reaffirms that effective batching is essential for good computational efficiency and that the DLT-guided KMS provides robust, transparent security with a manageable impact on performance. This investigation underscores that uniting homomorphic encryption with distributed ledger technology offers a truly viable path for creating trustworthy, privacy-respecting AI systems in healthcare.
