N2  - The proliferation of Whole Genome Sequencing (WGS) presents unprecedented opportunities for biomedical research and personalized medicine, alongside significant privacy challenges. Genomic data, inherently sensitive and unique, necessitates robust frameworks that balance research utility with individual privacy. This is possible if research results can be promptly returned to individual contributors. This paper outlines a distributed architecture for the de-identification, authorization, and secure updating of genomic data. The proposed architecture integrates advanced Privacy-Enhancing Technologies (PETs). It incorporates multi-layered authorization mechanisms enhanced consent management and auditability. Furthermore, the architecture addresses the integration of heterogeneous genomic data formats through adapters and a data bus, leveraging GA4GH standards to promote interoperability. Finally, it details mechanisms for the secure updating of de-identified data, including key management for encrypted data and dynamic consent frameworks for user notification regarding data status and research findings. This comprehensive approach aims to provide a scalable, secure, and ethical solution for managing distributed genomic data in the WGS era and most importantly, to protect the rights of the owner of genetic data.
