N2  - This study establishes a framework for assessing new quality productive forces by using panel data from 30 provincial-level administrative regions in China from 2012 to 2022. By applying two-way fixed effects and mediated effects models, this study systematically analyses the impact of financial agglomeration on new quality productive forces, focusing on regional differences. The results show that financial agglomeration significantly promotes the development of new quality productive forces, with regional heterogeneity. Moreover, industrial structure optimisation and market demand expansion are mediating factors. These findings provide a theoretical basis for optimising the allocation of financial resources and promoting the development of new quality productive forces. The study also makes policy recommendations, including deepening financial supply-side reform, promoting industrial integration cooperation mechanisms, and implementing region-specific strategies.
