N2  - Broadcast Automatic Dependent Surveillance–Broadcast (ADS–B) system utilizes satellite navigation and wireless broadcasting to provide real-time flight data such as aircraft position, speed, and altitude, enhancing pilots’ situational awareness and the precision of air traffic management. However, due to its open broadcast communication method, ADS–B is susceptible to security threats such as message eavesdropping, data interference, message forgery, and tampering. This paper analyzes the working principles and current applications of ADS–B while discussing security measures based on methods such as multilateration, timestamps, and traffic modeling. Finally, this paper proposes data security assurance strategies for ADS–B by integrating blockchain, quantum encryption, and AI technologies.
