SN  - 9798400718748
DO  - 10.1145/3773365.3773619
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1145/3773365.3773619
N2  - The rapid proliferation of the Internet of Things (IoT) has introduced unprecedented security risks across a wide range of applications, from smart homes to industrial control systems. This survey provides a systematic examination of the evolving IoT security landscape and underscores the transformative role of Artificial Intelligence (AI) in reshaping defense mechanisms. We begin by categorizing the major attack vectors - including distributed denial-of-service, malware infiltration, and data spoofing - and analyzing their impact on resource-constrained IoT devices. Building on this threat model, we review cutting-edge AI-driven approaches, such as machine learning-based anomaly detection, deep learning for intrusion prevention, and federated learning frameworks for privacy-preserving collaboration. Key limitations, including dataset scarcity, model interpretability, and vulnerability to adversarial attacks, are critically evaluated. Furthermore, we propose a cross-domain collaboration paradigm that integrates edge computing, cloud orchestration, and cross-industry knowledge sharing to strengthen system resilience. By identifying open challenges and outlining future research directions, this work aims to provide a comprehensive roadmap for researchers and practitioners dedicated to advancing AI-empowered IoT security.
ER  - 
