DO  - 10.1145/3764206.3764336
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1145/3764206.3764336
N2  - Vocational education faces a awkward situation nowadays - schools teach stuff that companies don't really need, while companies need skills that schools don't teach much. This supply-demand mismatch seriously affects the integration of education and industry. This paper designed a skill mapping system based on knowledge graph to solve this problem. The core idea of system is quite simple - just transform the skills needed by companies and the content taught by schools into knowledge graphs, and then match them together. Specifically, we first grab industry skill data from job sites, company job descriptions and other places to build industry skill knowledge graph. Also, we extract teaching content from school curriculum outlines, textbooks and other materials to build education resource knowledge graph. The most key part is a multidimensional mapping algorithm we designed, which not only looks at text similarity, but also analyzes graph structure relationships and node attributes to accurately connect content from both sides. Experiments were conducted in three areas: IT, manufacturing and service industries. The IT field got best results with F1 value of 0.86, while service industry was slightly worse at 0.76. The system has been deployed in several vocational colleges, helping schools adjust curriculum, improving course coverage by 5.8 percentage points. Although system still has room for improvement in handling emerging skills and soft skills, it provides a practical technical solution for industry-education integration overall.
