CY  - New York, NY, USA
SN  - 9798400713491
DO  - 10.1145/3762249.3762306
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1145/3762249.3762306
N2  - In the context of rapid development of financial technology, credit risk control of small and medium-sized banks is constrained by data silos and sample imbalance. This paper proposes a co-construction scheme of credit risk control model for small and medium-sized banks based on federated transfer learning, and designs an improved federated adversarial transfer learning algorithm. The algorithm strengthens the extraction of key risk features through the attention mechanism, optimizes cross-domain knowledge transfer by using adversarial networks, and realizes model aggregation by adaptive weight adjustment. The experiment uses the UCI credit data set and simulated small and medium-sized bank data, and is carried out under the FATE federated learning framework. The algorithm is compared with five algorithms including FedAvg and XGBoost. The results show that the accuracy of the algorithm reaches 92.3%, which is 7.8 percentage points higher than FedAvg and 5.2 percentage points higher than XGBoost; the recall rate is 89.5%, which is 6.2 and 4.1 percentage points higher than the comparison algorithm respectively; the F1 value reaches 90.9%, which is the best. The model converged stably within 150 iterations, and the convergence speed was 30% higher than that of the traditional algorithm. The privacy attack experiment showed that the scheme could reduce the success rate of member reasoning attacks to 3.2%, significantly protecting data privacy. The experiment confirmed that the scheme effectively improved the performance of the credit risk control model of small and medium-sized banks and achieved safe and efficient model co-construction.
