N2  - The Internet of Things-enabled (IoT-enabled) consumer electronics have accelerated consumer data collection, transmission, and sharing. In reality, IoT-enabled consumer electronics are organized into distinct trust domains based on their distribution and characteristics. Ciphertext policy attribute-based encryption (CP-ABE) is a promising approach for ensuring the security of cross-domain data sharing. However, CP-ABE based on bilinear pairing is theoretically vulnerable to potential quantum attacks, and current CP-ABE based on the ring learning with error (CP-ABERLWE) schemes suffer from limitations in efficiency, privacy, and dynamism. In view of the above problems, building upon a previous fundamental CP-ABERLWE scheme, this paper proposes an attribute-based encryption cross-domain data sharing scheme based on RLWE. We design an online/offline encryption algorithm based on RLWE and linear secret-sharing scheme, enhancing the encryption efficiency for IoT-enabled consumer electronics. The online/offline encryption also enables devices to complete policy hiding during the offline phase, thereby reducing the impact of the policy hiding algorithm on the encryption efficiency. We design effective update keys to implement an effective RLWE-based indirect revocation algorithm. We develop an RLWE-based policy hiding algorithm that hides attribute values containing sensitive information within ciphertexts. We introduce the concept of realistic cross-domain data sharing, whereby public parameters and master keys configured in different domains are different. We propose a ciphertext parameter conversion method to apply the designed CP-ABERLWE scheme to realistic cross-domain data sharing scenarios. Through theoretical analysis and simulation, our scheme is sIND-CPA secure based on the decision RLWE problem. Furthermore, our scheme has low storage and computational costs.
