N2  - Background and Problem Formulation: To handle huge data for diagnosis of data, Medical healthcare centers are recognized as an advantageous construction. Medical data privacy is in danger as in the case of traditional machine learning algorithms. These algorithms faced challenges in securing data from leakage. Federated learning ensures privacy while contextualizing critical data to protect user information in smart healthcare. Methods: This paper proposes a novel Blockchain based federated learning approach to network security analysis using blockchain and Federated learning to enhance data privacy and integrity in healthcare IoT environments. Initially, the gathered Internet of Medical Things (IoMT) data is fed as input to the novel Blockchain based federated learning. This method involves Cluster-Based Aggregation Scheme at the edge node to effectively detect and mitigate faults. To ensure the confidentiality of the model parameters and client data, a mutual key agreement is incorporated. The implementation of a secure common session key computation and mutual authentication paradigm enables secure communication between data owners and recipients. Using blockchain, global updates are managed and propagated to offer a transparent, tamper-proof, and decentralized mechanism. Furthermore, it explores discrete-time continuous-dilation wavelet transforms and quantum neural networks for data processing and analysis, showcasing their potential to enhance security and efficiency in cloud network environments. By leveraging discrete-time continuous-dilation wavelet transforms, healthcare data can be processed in a way that preserves its integrity while safeguarding it against unauthorized access. By combining the principles of quantum computing and neural networks, quantum neural networks process and analyze complex healthcare data with unparalleled efficiency and accuracy. Results: At last, the superiority of the proposed method is highlighted by performing comparative analyses in terms of accuracy, precision, recall, F1-measure, latency, and throughput. The results demonstrate that the proposed approach achieves high reliability in securing healthcare data and is superior to existing techniques. Conclusion: The efficacy of the proposed method is ensured, displaying that it can enhance the security of data, and minimize drawbacks related to traditional healthcare data-sharing approach. Therefore, the combination of federated learning, blockchain, and edge computing offers an extensive solution to share healthcare information securely. Significance of the achieved results: The achieved results are highly significant and demonstrate the robustness and effectiveness of the Blockchain-based Federated Learning approach in securing IoT healthcare systems. The achieved accuracy value of 98.73% indicates that the proposed model is highly reliable in making correct predictions. The achieved high precision (98.62%) ensures the ability of the proposed model to minimize false positive rates to reduce unnecessary alarms and interventions. The obtained high recall value of 98.23% is essential to minimize missed diagnoses. High throughput is essential to process more data. The low latency indicates a quick response of the proposed model, and it is essential to monitor emergency cases.
