N2  - The pharmaceutical industry faces significant cybersecurity challenges, with increasing threats to sensitive data, intellectual property, and patient information. Traditional cybersecurity models, including signature-based and threshold-based intrusion detection systems (IDS), often fail to address the dynamic and evolving nature of cyber threats. This paper introduces a novel Artificial Intelligence (AI-driven) cryptographic system designed to enhance cybersecurity in the pharmaceutical sector, integrating advanced AI techniques such as reinforcement learning, game theory, and C*-algebra to optimize resource allocation, improve threat detection, and enhance cryptographic protocols. Through comprehensive evaluation, the AI model demonstrates superior performance over traditional methods, achieving a detection rate of 97.4%, significantly reducing false positive rates (2.6%) and response time (50ms), and attaining an F1-score of 0.95. Specifically, in the CICIDS 2017 dataset, the AI model reached a detection rate of 97.4%, compared to 85.2% for traditional IDS, while MITRE ATT&CK saw a detection rate of 91.5% and a false positive rate of 12.0%. The MIMIC-III dataset achieved 93.0% detection with a false positive rate of 6.5%, and in the UWF-ZeekData22 dataset, the AI model recorded a detection rate of 96.0% and a false positive rate of 3.5%. The AI model’s ability to continuously adapt to emerging cyber threats makes it a future-proof solution for the pharmaceutical industry, with scalability ensuring applicability across various organizational sizes. Future research directions include integrating blockchain, cloud computing, and post-quantum cryptography to further strengthen system resilience. This paper presents a scalable, adaptive, and efficient solution to address growing cybersecurity challenges in the pharmaceutical industry, ensuring critical data protection in an increasingly complex threat landscape.
